		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id7210183682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>10:15.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Subpoena for production of documentary evidence</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A party may compel a third party to produce at trial books, papers, documents, or tangible things in his possession by a subpoena for production of documentary evidence. <eos/>
						<bos/>Georgia law now conforms with federal practice, and the clerk will issue a blank subpoena to a party requesting it, who may fill it in before service.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7ae3757074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In response to a timely written motion, the court may quash or modify the subpoena if it is unreasonable and oppressive. <eos/>
						<bos/>Also, the court may condition denial of the motion upon the advancement by the person in whose behalf the subpoena is issued of the reasonable cost of producing the books, papers, documents, or tangible things.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7ae3757174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Subpoenas may be enforced through contempt sanctions and fines and secondary evidence is admissible when the primary item is unsuccessfully sought.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7ae39c8074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A subpoena duces tecum may be issued by a client against an attorney in subsequent litigation for documents in the legal file.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7ae39c8174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
		<footnote.block>
			<footnote ID="I7ae3757074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>1</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-13-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I1756fe0074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-13-21</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7ae3757174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>2</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-13-23" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I1757733074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-13-23(b)(2)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Items that are neither pertinent nor relevant need not be produced under subpoena to produce documents or tangible things. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-serial-number="2009625520" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1757c15274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Walker v. Bruhn, 281 Ga. App. 149, 635 S.E.2d 322 (2006)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>The cellular phone records of defendant, who allegedly followed and photographed plaintiff on a frequent basis, were not reasonably calculated to lead to the discovery of admissible evidence regarding the intrusiveness of defendant&apos;s behavior. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-serial-number="2011203382" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1758368274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Anderson v. Mergenhagen, 283 Ga. App. 546, 642 S.E.2d 105 (2007)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Trial court was correct in denying motion to modify subpoena where hospital wanted to limit defendant in tort suit from discovery of medical rates and charges to third parties; wide latitude is given to parties to make discovery. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-serial-number="2043699767" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I175884a274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">WellStar Kennestone Hospital v. Roman, 344 Ga. App. 375, 810 S.E.2d 600 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7ae39c8074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>3</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-13-26" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I1758f9d074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-13-26</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>However, an order under this Code section must be definite enough to allow a party to purge itself of the contempt. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-serial-number="2042972471" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I175947f274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Rocker v. First Bank of Dalton, 343 Ga. App. 501, 806 S.E.2d 884 (2017)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7ae39c8174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>4</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017213" w-serial-number="2003359832" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1759bd2274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Swift, Currie, McGhee &amp; Hiers v. Henry, 276 Ga. 571, 581 S.E.2d 37 (2003)</cite.query>
							.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
